def label(x,y,t):
    """
    Args:
    x (str): x-axis
    y (str): y-axis
    t (str): main title
    
    Returns:
    None
    """
    
    plt.xlabel(x)
    plt.ylabel(y)
    plt.title(t)
    plt.show()

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183412 entries in the dataset with 16 features(columns) namley:(duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip)

  • There were missing data in the dataset : start_station_id - 197, start_station_name - 197, end_station_id - 197, end_station_name - 197, member_birth_year - 8265, member_gender - 8265

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

> I am interested in figuring out what features are best for:¶

  • How long does the average trip take?
  • Does the above depend on if a user is a subscriber or customer?
  • Is gender associated with bike sharing for all trips?
  • What group of user-type patronise Ford GoBike System the most?
  • Does age group of members (count of member_birth-year) have a relationship with the duration of bike ride trips?

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I think that user type(subscriber or customer) will have a strong effect on how long the average trip take. Also I think gender might not neccesarily affect the bike-sharing for all trips. Again, I also think member's age might affect the how long (duration) of the average trip.

Question 2: What the age (using date of birth) distribution of users?¶

#get current tick labels

From the bargraph plot, the year 1988 recorded the highest count among member_birth_year, followed by years 1993, 1989, 1990; to mention but a few respctively. It can also be observed that year 0 was the sixth highest member_birht_year. Member_birth year 0 represents birth years of members(user_type collectively) which were either not recorded or available in the data

Question 12: Is there a relationship associated with member gender, age_of_member and end_station_longitude?¶

In [34]:
#creating a categorical age variable using floor division.
df['age_category'] = ((df['age_of_member']//10)*10).astype(int)

#setting plot dimension
plt.figure(figsize=[14,6])

sb.stripplot(data=df, x='age_category', y='end_station_longitude', hue='member_gender', 
            jitter=0.35, dodge=True, size=1)
plt.title('Relationship between member gender, age_of_member and end_station_longitude');

From the plot, it is observable that members of all genders with their ages less than 90years had lots of data points counts which were concentrated their respective end station longitude. This goes on to question " Do older people not finish or complete their ride to their destinations(end stations)?"; because the graph depicts fewer data points for members of ages 100years and above.

Question 14: Is there a relationship between gender of member, duration of ride and age of member?¶

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • It was observable that members of all genders with their ages less than 90years had lots of data points counts which were concentrated their respective end station longitude. This goes on to question " Do older people not finish or complete their ride to their destinations(end stations)?"; because the graph depicts fewer data points for members of ages 100years and above. It was later confirmed that it is possible that either older members of ages 100 and above are fewer when it comes to reaching their ride end station or fewer older people actually patronise Ford Bike System

  • It was also observed that both customer and subscriber user types of age less than 80 years are associated with high count of bike ride duration.

  • Again, from the scatter plot, it appears that younger ages (ages less than 80 years) of all genders are associated with higher duration(seconds) of ride.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Yes, there was surprising interactions between the features. The younger the age of member regardless the gender, the longer their bike ride duration.

Conclusions¶

From the exploratory analysis performed, It was found that

  • The user-types of Ford GoBike were mainly Customers and Subscribers. In terms of sex of members, the gender was categorically Male, Female and Other.
  • Males formed the highest population of members, followed by Females and Other genders respectively.
  • Members (user types) of younger ages were associated with high duration of bike ride durations whereas older aged members recorded short ride durations.
